data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code in EF Core 10. Here's each one:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes `Func<>`, not `Expression<Func<>>`

Your hand-built expression tree **won't compile** because the overload now accepts a plain lambda. The fix is dramatically simpler:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

Delete all the `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` / `Expression.Parameter` machinery.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Sibling complex types with same property names now get uniquified columns.** Your `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously shared one `Street` column (silent data corruption risk). EF 10 appends a number (e.g. `Street`, `Street1`). To keep explicit names:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use the full path.** Your `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` column changes from `BillingAddress_City` → `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To preserve the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

> ⚠️ Both changes affect **existing migrations**. After upgrading, run `dotnet ef migrations add FixColumnNames` — if the generated migration renames columns you don't want renamed, pin names with `HasColumnName` as shown above.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gains a `string logCommandText` parameter (for redacted SQL logging). Add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (may have constants redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual executed SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** methods on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.
